Leaders have called for concerted efforts to unite warring communities in the county.  The officials spoke yesterday as the world marked International Peace Day.  The county recently hit headlines after suspected bandits invaded the area, killing eight people, including two police officers and forcing hundreds out of their homes.  More than 500 livestock have been stolen in the last month.    Locals want livestock allowed to graze in ADC farm linked to Ruto  Doctors' union want Governor Ndiritu Muriithi cited for contempt  Order! Kaparo on Raila's fifth stab at presidency, the big Laikipia lie and dancing politicians  Laikipia clashes: Does Jubilee know its core mission? Speaking in Rumuruti town, Governor Ndiritu Muriithi said he would lead a team of community elders to sensitise the locals on living peacefully.  "I will personally be responsible for these peace meetings. I cannot sit back and watch as my people are killed by bandits," he said.  Muriithi said his administration was working closely with the national government to ensure peace is restored in the area. Among the areas affected are Ol Moran, Wangwaci, Matwiku, Survey and Kamwenje.  Newly appointed County Commissioner Joseph Kanyiri told parents to take their children to school as peace has been restored.   CS Fred Matiang'i says the Government is committed to addressing the insecurity in Laikipia County  Kamket Kizimbani: Mbunge wa Tiaty amekamatwa jana kuhusiana na mapigano eneo la Laikipia  Laikipia county Gov't enters into a lease agreement to enable it scale-up infrastructure development By Brian Otieno and Judah Ben-Hur | 6 hours ago By Amos Kareithi | 12 hours ago By Moses Nyamori | 12 hours ago By Chebet Birir | 12 hours ago